Thieves have swiped personal data such as Social Security numbers, birth dates and addresses for more than a decade to gain access to bank accounts and credit cards.
The ability of suspected serial killer Angel Maturino Resendiz to avoid capture with phony identification cards illustrates the need for a more secure Social Security document, a U.S. congressman said Thursday.
An identity theft hotline established last year by the Federal Trade Commission reports getting 400 calls a week.
As technology advances, criminals are finding new ways to steal and exploit personal information _ identity fraud, as the practice is known.
